  "prompt": "How Indian Air Force Chief SP Tyagi was involved in Augusta Westland Scam?",
  "response": "The Augusta Westland scam involved allegations of corruption in the purchase of VVIP helicopters by the Indian government from the Italian company Finmeccanica's subsidiary, Augusta Westland. The controversy began when it was revealed that substantial kickbacks were allegedly paid to secure the deal.\n\nAir Chief Marshal S.P. Tyagi, who served as the Chief of Air Staff of the Indian Air Force from 2004 to 2007, was implicated in the case due to accusations concerning his alleged involvement in the decision-making process of the procurement. The allegations suggested that Tyagi and his family had received benefits in connection with the deal.\n\nInvestigations by various agencies, including the Central Bureau of Investigation (CBI) and the Enforcement Directorate (ED), focused on the roles of several individuals in the procurement process, including Tyagi. In particular, it was alleged that Tyagi altered specifications to allow Augusta Westland\u2019s helicopters to qualify for the contract.\n\nHowever, Tyagi has denied the allegations, and there have been no conclusive findings of guilt against him individually. The case drew significant media attention and led to wider examination of defense procurement processes in India, highlighting issues of corruption and transparency.\n\nFor the most current information, it\u2019s essential to refer to the latest reports, as legal matters and investigations can evolve over time.",
